# Cybernetics Agent — Comprehensive Tutorial

Cybernetics Agent is a personal autonomous agent that lives on a machine you control (laptop, VPS, GPU box, serverless), keeps persistent memory + learned skills across sessions, and can be reached from the CLI and 20+ messaging platforms (Telegram, Discord, Slack, WhatsApp, Signal, email) through a single gateway.

Below is an end-to-end walkthrough.

---
## 1. Install

**macOS / Linux / WSL2 / Android Termux**
```bash
curl -fsSL https://raw.githubusercontent.com/Avarile/cybernetics-agent/master/scripts/install.sh | bash
source ~/.zshrc      # or ~/.bashrc
```

**Windows (PowerShell, no admin required)**
```powershell
iex (irm https://raw.githubusercontent.com/Avarile/cybernetics-agent/master/scripts/install.ps1)
```
The Windows installer bundles Python 3.11, Node.js, ripgrep, ffmpeg, and a portable Git Bash (~45 MB).

**From source (dev / contributor):**
```bash
git clone https://github.com/Avarile/cybernetics-agent.git
cd cybernetics-agent
./setup-cybernetics.sh
```

Verify with:
```bash
cybernetics doctor
```

---
## 2. First-time setup

Run the setup wizard to configure provider, model, tools, persona, messaging platforms, and memory:

```bash
cybernetics setup
```

Config lives in:
- macOS/Linux/WSL2: `~/.cybernetics/`
- Windows: `%LOCALAPPDATA%\cybernetics\`

Key files inside that directory:

| File          | Purpose                          |
|---------------|----------------------------------|
| `config.yaml` | main settings                    |
| `SOUL.md`     | persona / personality            |
| `MEMORY.md`   | persistent agent memory          |
| `USER.md`     | what the agent knows about you   |
| `.env`        | API keys & secrets               |
| `skills/`     | learned + imported skills        |

---
## 3. Chat with it

```bash
cybernetics
```

You get a terminal UI with multiline editing, slash-command autocomplete, and streaming tool output. Useful in-chat commands (these work in CLI and every messaging platform):

| Command                            | Effect                                         |
|------------------------------------|------------------------------------------------|
| `/new` or `/reset`                 | start a fresh conversation                     |
| `/model provider:model-name`       | switch model on the fly                        |
| `/personality <name>`              | switch persona                                 |
| `/retry`, `/undo`                  | redo or remove last turn                       |
| `/compress`                        | summarize/compress long context                |
| `/usage`                           | token & cost usage                             |
| `/insights --days 7`               | self-generated reflections on recent activity  |
| `/skills`                          | list learned skills                            |
| `/<skill-name>`                    | invoke a skill                                 |
| Ctrl+C (CLI) / `/stop` (messaging) | interrupt current work                         |

---
## 4. Pick / change models

Cybernetics is provider-agnostic:

```bash
cybernetics model           # interactive picker
cybernetics config set model openrouter:anthropic/claude-3.5-sonnet
cybernetics config set default_provider openrouter
```

Supported providers include OpenRouter (200+ models), OpenAI, Anthropic, NovitaAI, NVIDIA NIM (Nemotron), Hugging Face, Xiaomi MiMo, z.ai/GLM, Kimi/Moonshot, MiniMax. Keys go in `~/.cybernetics/.env`, e.g.:

```
OPENAI_API_KEY=sk-...
ANTHROPIC_API_KEY=sk-ant-...
OPENROUTER_API_KEY=...
```

Or via env vars:
```bash
export CYBERNETICS_MODEL="openai:gpt-4o"
export CYBERNETICS_PROVIDER="openrouter"
```

---
## 5. Tools (40+ built-in)

```bash
cybernetics tools           # interactive selector
```

Categories: web search/browsing (Firecrawl), image gen (FAL), TTS (OpenAI), code execution, file ops, and a terminal tool with 6 selectable execution backends:

| Backend     | When to use                                  |
|-------------|----------------------------------------------|
| local       | quickest, runs on your box                   |
| Docker      | sandboxed, hardened containers               |
| SSH         | hand work off to a remote server             |
| Singularity | HPC clusters                                 |
| Modal       | serverless Python, hibernates between calls  |
| Daytona     | serverless with persistence                  |

Switch backend in `config.yaml` or via `cybernetics config set terminal.backend docker`.

---
## 6. Skills system (the "grows with you" part)

Skills are procedural memory — recipes the agent writes for itself and improves over time. They live in `~/.cybernetics/skills/` and follow the open agentskills.io standard, so you can share them.

```bash
/skills                # list
/<skill-name>          # run or inspect
```

After finishing a non-trivial task, the agent periodically "nudges" itself to persist what it learned as a reusable skill. You can also hand-write a skill (a folder with a `SKILL.md` + supporting files) and drop it into `~/.cybernetics/skills/`.

---
## 7. Memory system

Three layers, all under `~/.cybernetics/`:

1. `MEMORY.md` — durable facts/procedures, FTS5-indexed for fast retrieval.
2. `USER.md` — your profile (preferences, style, constraints), refined via dialectic user modeling.
3. Session search — full-text search + LLM summarization across past conversations.

Day-to-day habits:
- Run `/compress` when a session gets long.
- Let the agent update `MEMORY.md` after gnarly tasks; review occasionally.
- Edit `USER.md` directly if you want to seed preferences.

---
## 8. Messaging gateway (Telegram / Discord / Slack / …)

This is what lets the agent reach you anywhere:

```bash
cybernetics gateway setup    # enter credentials per platform
cybernetics gateway start    # run the bridge (often kept alive on a VPS)
```

Once running, all the `/`-commands above work inside DMs. The gateway is also what receives scheduled task deliveries.

---
## 9. Scheduling (natural-language cron)

The scheduler runs inside the gateway process and accepts plain English:

```
every day at 9:00 AM -> send-report
every night at 2:00 AM -> backup-databases
every monday at 10:00 AM -> run-security-audit
```

Output is delivered to whichever platform you specify (Telegram chat, Discord channel, email, etc.). Because the gateway can run on a $5 VPS, your laptop doesn't have to be on.

---
## 10. Subagents / delegation

Cybernetics can spawn isolated subagents — each with its own conversation, its own execution environment, and zero context cost to the parent. Use them for:

- parallel workstreams (research several topics at once),
- long tool chains you don't want polluting your main thread,
- Python scripts that call agent tools over RPC.

In normal chat you just ask: *"Spawn a subagent to scrape X while you keep working on Y."* For programmatic use, RPC-style calls into the tool layer are supported.

---
## 11. Web dashboard

A browser-based dashboard is available for monitoring sessions, browsing memory, and inspecting tool calls:

```bash
cybernetics dashboard --no-open    # serves on 127.0.0.1:9119
```

Open `http://127.0.0.1:9119` in a browser. Drop `--no-open` to auto-launch.

## 11.1 Gateway

```bash
cybernetics gateway start # start the gateway process
cybernetics gateway stop  # stop the gateway process
```

---
## 12. Troubleshooting

```bash
cybernetics doctor          # environment + config diagnosis
cybernetics config set ...  # tweak any setting
```

If things break after an update, check `~/.cybernetics/config.yaml` and `~/.cybernetics/.env` first, then rerun `cybernetics setup`.

